      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ μετὰ τὸ ἀποθανεῖν Εσερων ἦλθεν Χαλεβ εἰς Εφραθα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; “And after Hezron’s death Caleb went to Ephrath.” Some very slight changes in the Hebrew, affecting only three letters of the entire sentence, will give the sense, “And after Hezron’s death Caleb went in to Ephrath, the wife of his father Hezron (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 2:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and she bare him Ash-hur, father (founder, or chief) of Tekoa.” (Comp. ",
