  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 24.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The remaining verse of this section brings another point of difficulty unsolved yet. No place ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Caleb-ephratah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is known, and no sort of accounting for Hezron dying anywhere but in Egypt, whither he went with Jacob (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is producible. The Vulgate has ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Ingressus est Caleb ad Ephratam",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but our Hebrew text cannot be made to justify it, if for nothing else, for want of a preposition ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אֶל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " before \"Ephrata.\" This reading of the Vulgate has suggested to others that by a slight but still gratuitous alteration of our Hebrew text ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "בָא",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " might be substituted for the preposition ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "בְּ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " prefixed to the name of Caleb; but upon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "that",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " showing we have to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "suppose",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that Caleb did leave Egypt on his own account and travel to Ephratah, and then there fails any strong connection (but see Septuagint, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "loc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") between that fact and what is said about ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Abiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Still, the explanation might receive some countenance from the fact that it is said that Abiah's son became the father - or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "founder - of",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "founder - ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "of",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Tekoa",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Tekoa",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a place near Bethlehem, in South Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 30:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Bertheau has at this point suggested that Caleb-ephratah, instead of being included in Neger-Caleb, may rather, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "distinction",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from it, designate the northern portion of the territory of Caleb. The solution of the problem will probably not yield to anything but a justly restored text. 1 Chronicles 2:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After the death of Hezron there was born to him by his wife Abiah (the third wife, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") another son, Ashur, the father of Tekoa, whose descendants are enumerated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 4:5-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Hezron's death took place אפרתה בּכלב, \"in Caleb Ephrathah.\" This expression is obscure. According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 30:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a part of the Negeb (south country) of Judah was called Negeb Caleb, as it belonged to the family of Caleb. According to this analogy, the town or village in which Caleb dwelt with his wife Ephrath may have been called Caleb of Ephrathah, if Ephrath had brought this place as a dower to Caleb, as in the case mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Ephrathah, or Ephrath, was the ancient name of Bethlehem (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 33:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 48:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and with it the name of Caleb's wife Ephrath (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is unquestionably connected; probably she was so called after her birthplace. If this supposition be well founded, then Caleb of Ephrathah would be the little town of Bethlehem. Ashur is called father (אבי) of Tekoa, i.e., lord and prince, as the chief of the inhabitants of Tekoa, now Tekua, two hours south of Bethlehem (vide on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:59",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]